1. Introductory

The S&P 500 (Standard & Poors 500) is a stock market index that tracks the performance of 500 of the largest publicly traded companies in the U.S. It is widely regarded as one of the best indicators of the overall health of the U.S. stock market and economy.In this project, we apply Metas Prophet forecasting model to predict future trends of the S&P 500. The objectives of this study are:
1. Explore the historical trends of the S&P 500 using time series decomposition.
2. Build a forecasting model using the Prophet library in R.
3. Evaluate the models predictive accuracy by comparing it with actual market movements.
4. Interpret key trends and seasonality components, such as daily, weekly, and yearly cycles.

4. Prophet model predictions

4.1 Modelling and Forecasting

# Training 
model <- prophet::prophet(SnP_500_df)
## Disabling daily seasonality. Run prophet with daily.seasonality=TRUE to override this.
# Generate data for the next year
Future <- prophet::make_future_dataframe(model, periods = 365, freq = "day")
Forecast <- predict(model, Future)

# Plotting forecast results
plot(model, Forecast) +
    ggplot2::ggtitle("S&P 500 Stock Price Forecast for 2025") + 
    ggplot2::labs(x = "Date", y = "Closing Price") + 
    ggplot2::theme_minimal()

The black dots represent actual S&P 500 historical prices. The blue line represents the predicted trend for 2025. The shaded blue area is the confidence interval.

The model predicts a upward movement in the SnP_500 in 2025. The S&P 500 is forecasted to move to around 7500 points by the end of 2025. The forecast shows wider confidence intervals as we move further into the future.

4.2 Plot forecast components (trend & seasonality)

prophet::prophet_plot_components(model, Forecast)

The trend component shows a steady upward movement in the S&P 500, but there is a drop during 2022. The long-term trend is upwards. The blue shaded region represents the uncertainty interval, which indicates higher prediction uncertainty over time.

The weekly seasonality shows how the S&P 500 behaves across the days of the week. From Monday to Friday, there is a negative or stable performance. and the drop and climb on Sunday and Saturday is useless. Because there is no trading. The Saturday and Sunday effects should be ignored.

The yearly seasonality represents repeating yearly patterns in the S&P 500. It fluctuates from January to September, then starts to decline, and doesnt start to pick up until November

5.2 Plot and compare actual data with predicted data

Forecast$ds <- as.Date(Forecast$ds)  # Convert to Date format


# Merge actual and predicted data
Comparison_df <- left_join(SnP_500_df_25, Forecast, by = "ds")

Comparison_df$y <- as.numeric(gsub(",", "", Comparison_df$y))
Comparison_df$yhat <- as.numeric(gsub(",", "", Comparison_df$yhat))

Comparison_df <- na.omit(Comparison_df)

ggplot(Comparison_df, aes(x = ds)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = y, color = "Actual"), linewidth = 1, linetype = "solid") + 
  geom_line(aes(y = yhat, color = "Predicted"), linewidth = 1, linetype = "dashed") + 
  labs(title = "S&P 500 Actual and Predicted Prices (2025)",
       x = "Date", y = "Closing Price", color = "Legend") +  # Legend title
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma) +
  scale_color_manual(name = "Legend", values = c("Actual" = "blue", "Predicted" = "red")) +  # Custom legend
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

The actual price data looks a bit erratic, with sharp spikes and drops. this is because some of the data is missing. not in the dataset.
The predicted prices appear smooth and upward trending, which is expected from a forecasting model. However, the actual prices are not, it was struggling around 6000. the prediction overestimate the price. This may because some effect is not take under consideration.

6. Mathematical insight

Prophet model formula:

\[y(t) = g(t) + s(t) + h(t) + \epsilon_t\] g(t): Trend Component
s(t): Seasonal Component
h(t): Holiday Effects epsilon_t: Error Term

7. Conclusion and outlook

In this coursework, we utilized Facebooks Prophet model for time series forecasting. The analysis involved data preprocessing, visualization, and implementing Prophet to predict future values.

The results indicate that Prophet effectively captured the overall trend and seasonality of the dataset, making it a useful tool for forecasting. However, discrepancies between actual and predicted values suggest that factors such as external economic influences or data limitations may have impacted model accuracy.
